                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>German Wirehaired Pointers are medium to large-sized dogs. Males typically weigh between 60-70 pounds and stand about 24-26 inches tall at the shoulder, while females weigh around 45-65 pounds and stand about 21-24 inches tall.</p>',
                'size_description' => '<p>German Wirehaired Pointers are medium to large-sized dogs. Males typically weigh between 60-70 pounds and stand about 24-26 inches tall at the shoulder, while females weigh around 45-65 pounds and stand about 21-24 inches tall.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The breed is known for its distinctive, wiry coat, which is dense and water-resistant. This coat helps protect them from harsh weather and rough terrain during hunting. The color can vary, commonly found in combinations of liver and white or solid liver. Regular grooming is necessary to manage shedding and maintain the coat\'s health.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>German Wirehaired Pointers are known for their intelligence, loyalty, and energetic personality. They are friendly and affectionate with their families but may be reserved or cautious with strangers. These dogs are eager to please and incredibly trainable but require consistent and firm training to avoid stubbornness.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>GWHPs thrive in active households where they can receive ample physical and mental stimulation. They do best in homes with access to a yard, as they need regular exercise to stay healthy and happy. They are not ideal for apartment living unless they can access regular outdoor activity.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>German Wirehaired Pointers enjoy a range of activities, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks and outdoor play</li><li>Hunting and retrieving exercises</li><li>Obedience training and tricks</li><li>Participation in dog sports, such as agility or field trials</li><li>Scent work and tracking games</li></ul><p>Engaging them in regular exercise and mental challenges is critical for their well-being, as they are energetic dogs that thrive on both physical activity and companionship.</p>',
