            241 =>
            array (
                'id' => 263,
                'name' => 'Australian Shepherd',
                'slug' => 'australian-shepherd',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 15,
                'male_weight_max' => 30,
                'male_weight_min' => 20,
                'female_weight_max' => 25,
                'female_weight_min' => 17,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>Despite the name, the Australian Shepherd was actually developed in the United States in the 19th century. The breed was created by American ranchers who needed a versatile herding dog to work with livestock, particularly sheep. Their name is believed to come from the association with Basque shepherds who brought their dogs to America from Australia. Australian Shepherds quickly gained popularity for their intelligence, work ethic, and herding ability.</p>',
                'size_description' => '<p>Australian Shepherds are medium-sized dogs. Males typically weigh between 50-65 pounds and stand about 20-23 inches tall at the shoulder, while females usually weigh around 40-55 pounds and stand about 18-21 inches tall.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The breed has a medium-length double coat that is weather-resistant. The outer coat is straight or slightly wavy, while the undercoat is softer and denser. Australian Shepherds come in various colors, including black, blue merle, red, and red merle, often with white and tan markings. Regular grooming is essential to manage shedding and keep their coat healthy.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Australian Shepherds are known for their high energy levels, intelligence, and eagerness to please. They are loyal and protective of their families but can be wary of strangers, making them good watchdogs. Their playful and affectionate nature makes them great companions, especially with active families. Early socialization and training are essential due to their strong herding instincts.</p><p><br></p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Australian Shepherds thrive in an active lifestyle, requiring regular exercise and mental stimulation. They are best suited for homes with ample space to run and explore, such as those with large yards or access to open areas. They can adapt to various environments but do not do well as sedentary pets.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Australian Shepherds excel in numerous activities, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks, hikes, and runs</li><li>Herding and obedience training</li><li>Participation in dog sports such as agility, flyball, and disc dog competitions</li><li>Fetch and retrieving games</li><li>Mental challenges through puzzle toys and scent work</li></ul><p>Engaging Australian Shepherds in both physical and mental activities is crucial for their overall health and happiness, as they thrive on activity, structured tasks, and social interaction.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
