            250 =>
            array (
                'id' => 271,
                'name' => 'Portuguese Pointer',
                'slug' => 'portuguese-pointer',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 14,
                'male_weight_max' => 30,
                'male_weight_min' => 25,
                'female_weight_max' => 30,
                'female_weight_min' => 25,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Portuguese Pointer is an ancient breed, thought to have originated in Portugal over 500 years ago. It was bred primarily as a hunting dog, particularly for pointing and retrieving game birds. The breed was influenced by various hunting breeds, including the English Pointer and several local breeds. Historically, they have been valued for their keen sense of smell and ability to work in diverse terrains.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>Portuguese Pointers are medium-sized dogs. Typically, they weigh between 45 to 66 pounds (20 to 30 kg) and stand about 20 to 24 inches (51 to 61 cm) tall at the shoulder. Males generally tend to be larger than females.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The coat of the Portuguese Pointer is short and dense, providing protection against harsh weather. It is generally smooth and can come in various colors, including white, orange, liver, or a combination of these with spots. Regular grooming helps to remove loose hair and keep the coat healthy.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Portuguese Pointers are known for their friendly and affectionate nature. They are intelligent, energetic, and eager to please, making them trainable. Their friendly demeanor often makes them good with children and other pets. However, they can be strong-willed, requiring consistent training and socialization.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>This breed thrives in an active environment. They need ample exercise and mental stimulation to prevent boredom, which can lead to destructive behavior. They do best in homes where they have access to outdoor space, preferably with a family that enjoys outdoor activities.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Portuguese Pointers excel in various activities, including:</p><ul><li>Hunting and field trials</li><li>Agility and obedience training</li><li>Hiking and running</li><li>Swimming, as they are good swimmers</li><li>Participation in dog sports, including competitions</li></ul><p>Engaging in these activities helps fulfill their exercise needs and strengthens the bond with their owners.&nbsp;</p><p>If you\'re considering adopting a Portuguese Pointer, be prepared for an active lifestyle and a commitment to training and socialization.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            251 =>
            array (
                'id' => 273,
                'name' => 'Dalmatian',
                'slug' => 'dalmatian',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 11,
                'max_life' => 13,
                'male_weight_max' => 32,
                'male_weight_min' => 25,
                'female_weight_max' => 32,
                'female_weight_min' => 25,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Dalmatian has a rich and varied history that dates back several centuries. Originally from the Dalmatia region of Croatia, this breed has been used for various purposes, including as a carriage dog, firehouse mascot, and sentinel. Dalmatians were known for their ability to run alongside horse-drawn carriages, protecting them and their passengers. Over time, they gained popularity as show dogs and family pets, becoming well known for their distinctive spotted coat.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>Dalmatians are considered medium-sized dogs. They typically weigh between 45 to 70 pounds (20 to 32 kg) and stand around 19 to 24 inches (48 to 61 cm) tall at the shoulder. Males are generally larger and more robust than females.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>Dalmatians are famous for their short, dense, and glossy coat, which is primarily white with distinctive black or liver-colored spots. The coat is low-maintenance, requiring regular brushing to keep it clean and control shedding. It\'s important to note that Dalmatian puppies are born entirely white, and their spots develop as they grow.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Dalmatians are known for their lively, playful, and intelligent temperament. They are friendly, outgoing, and social, making them great companions for families. Their energetic nature means they often require consistent training and socialization from an early age. While typically good with children and other pets, they can sometimes exhibit a strong prey drive, particularly towards smaller animals.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Dalmatians thrive in active environments and do best with families that can provide plenty of exercise and stimulation. They are not well-suited for sedentary lifestyles and can develop behavioral issues if bored or isolated. A secure outdoor space is ideal for them to run and play safely.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Dalmatians enjoy a variety of activities, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks, runs, or jogs</li><li>Playing fetch and retrieving games</li><li>Participating in obedience and agility training</li><li>Engaging in canine sports such as rally and flyball</li><li>Swimming and other outdoor adventures</li></ul><p>Providing mental and physical challenges is crucial for keeping them happy and healthy.</p><p>If you’re considering bringing a Dalmatian into your home, be prepared for an energetic and affectionate companion that thrives on activity, companionship, and training to channel their instincts positively.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            252 =>
            array (
                'id' => 275,
                'name' => 'Pembroke Welsh Corgi',
                'slug' => 'pembroke-welsh-corgi',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 15,
                'male_weight_max' => 13,
                'male_weight_min' => 11,
                'female_weight_max' => 13,
                'female_weight_min' => 11,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Pembroke Welsh Corgi traces its origins to Wales, where it has been used as a herding dog for centuries. The breed is believed to have been brought to Wales by Flemish weavers in the 10th century. Corgis were primarily used to herd cattle and sheep, thanks to their agility and ability to nip at the heels of livestock. The Pembroke variety is distinguished by its docked tail and is often associated with British royalty, particularly Queen Elizabeth II, who has owned many Corgis throughout her life.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>Pembroke Welsh Corgis are small to medium-sized dogs. They typically weigh between 25 to 30 pounds (11 to 14 kg) and stand about 10 to 12 inches (25 to 30 cm) tall at the shoulder. Their unique build contributes to their reputation as nimble herders.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>Corgis have a double coat consisting of a dense undercoat and a weather-resistant outer coat. Their coat is medium-length and can come in various colors, including red, sable, fawn, black, and tan, often with white markings. Regular brushing, especially during shedding seasons, helps maintain their coat\'s health and reduces shedding.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Pembroke Welsh Corgis are known for their friendly, intelligent, and energetic temperament. They are affectionate and loyal, often forming strong bonds with their families. Corgis are known to be good with children and can also get along well with other pets if properly socialized. Their herding instincts can sometimes lead to stubbornness, so consistent training is important.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Corgis thrive in active households where they can participate in family activities. They are adaptable to different living situations, including apartments, as long as they receive daily exercise. However, because of their herding background, they require mental stimulation and physical activity to prevent boredom and maintain their well-being.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Pembroke Welsh Corgis enjoy a variety of activities, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks, runs, or play sessions&nbsp;</li><li>Participating in dog sports like obedience, agility, and herding trials</li><li>Engaging in interactive games, such as fetch or hide-and-seek</li><li>Socializing with other dogs and people</li><li>Training sessions to learn new tricks and commands</li></ul><p>Keeping a Corgi mentally and physically active is essential for a happy and well-adjusted pet.</p><p>If you’re considering a Pembroke Welsh Corgi, be prepared for a lively and loving companion that thrives on affection, activity, and training while also adding joy and charm to your household.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            253 =>
            array (
                'id' => 276,
                'name' => 'Karelian Bear Dog',
                'slug' => 'karelian-bear-dog',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 15,
                'male_weight_max' => 30,
                'male_weight_min' => 20,
                'female_weight_max' => 30,
                'female_weight_min' => 20,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Karelian Bear Dog is a Finnish breed originally used for hunting large game such as bears, moose, and lynxes. They are highly regarded for their courage, strength, and keen sense of smell. These dogs are known to be independent thinkers, which can make training a challenge, but they are also loyal and protective of their families.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>Karelian Bear Dogs are medium to large-sized dogs. Males typically weigh between 60 to 90 pounds (27 to 41 kg) and stand about 22 to 26 inches (56 to 66 cm) tall at the shoulder, while females are slightly smaller, weighing around 50 to 70 pounds (23 to 32 kg) and standing approximately 20 to 24 inches (51 to 61 cm) tall.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The coat of the Karelian Bear Dog is thick and double-layered, providing insulation against cold temperatures. The outer coat is rough and straight, while the undercoat is soft and dense. Common coat colors include black with white markings, as well as shades of brown and tan. Regular grooming is necessary to keep their coat healthy and to control shedding, especially during seasonal changes.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Karelian Bear Dogs are known for their strong, bold, and alert temperament. They are highly intelligent and independent, which can sometimes lead to stubbornness. While they are fiercely loyal to their family, they can be reserved or aloof with strangers. Early socialization and training are essential to help them develop into well-rounded pets. They can also have a strong prey drive due to their hunting background.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>This breed thrives in active environments and requires a significant amount of exercise to keep them physically and mentally stimulated. Karelian Bear Dogs are not well-suited for apartment living unless they receive plenty of outdoor time. They do best in homes with access to large yards or open spaces where they can run and explore.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Karelian Bear Dogs enjoy a variety of activities that cater to their physical and mental needs, including:</p><ul><li>Extensive daily walks, runs, and hikes</li><li>Participation in hunting and tracking activities&nbsp;</li><li>Obedience training and canine sports&nbsp;</li><li>Engaging in games that challenge their intelligence, such as puzzle toys</li><li>Exploring the outdoors and spending time in nature</li></ul><p>Providing these dogs with ample opportunities for exercise and stimulation is crucial for their well-being, as they can become bored and destructive if not properly engaged.</p><p>If you’re considering a Karelian Bear Dog as a pet, be prepared for a strong, loyal companion that thrives on activity and requires consistent training and socialization to flourish in a family environment.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            254 =>
            array (
                'id' => 277,
                'name' => 'Shetland Sheepdog',
                'slug' => 'shetland-sheepdog',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 15,
                'male_weight_max' => 14,
                'male_weight_min' => 9,
                'female_weight_max' => 14,
                'female_weight_min' => 9,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Shetland Sheepdog originated in the Shetland Islands of Scotland, where they were bred to herd sheep and other livestock. They are closely related to the Rough Collie but are smaller in size. Shelties are known for their strong work ethic, intelligence, and eagerness to learn, making them excellent companions in both family life and competitive dog sports.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>Shetland Sheepdogs are small to medium-sized dogs. They typically weigh between 30 to 45 pounds (14 to 20 kg) and stand about 13 to 16 inches (33 to 41 cm) tall at the shoulder. Males are generally larger than females.</p>',
            'coat_description' => '<p>The Sheltie\'s coat is one of its most distinctive features. They have a double coat consisting of a dense, soft undercoat and a longer, straight outer coat. Common coat colors include blue merle, sable, tri-color (black, brown, and white), and black and white. Regular grooming is necessary to keep their coat clean and free from mats, as they shed year-round and have heavier shedding periods.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Shelties are known for their friendly, intelligent, and loyal temperament. They are highly trainable and eager to please their owners but can sometimes be shy or reserved around strangers. Shelties are generally good with children and other pets, especially if socialized from an early age. Their herding instincts can lead to behaviors such as nipping and barking, so consistent training and socialization are crucial.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Shetland Sheepdogs thrive in active households and require regular exercise to stay happy and healthy. They do well in homes with access to a yard for play and exploration but can also adapt to apartment living if they receive sufficient exercise. Daily mental stimulation is also important to prevent boredom.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Shelties enjoy a variety of activities that engage their minds and bodies, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks, runs, or play sessions</li><li>Participation in dog sports such as agility, obedience, herding trials, and flyball</li><li>Interactive games, including fetch and puzzle-solving</li><li>Training sessions to learn new tricks and commands</li><li>Socialization opportunities with other dogs and at dog parks</li></ul><p>Keeping a Shetland Sheepdog engaged and active is essential for their overall well-being and happiness.&nbsp;</p><p>If you’re considering bringing a Shetland Sheepdog into your home, be prepared for a loving, intelligent companion that thrives on teaching and learning, and enjoys participating in family activities.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            255 =>
            array (
                'id' => 279,
                'name' => ' Goldendoodle',
                'slug' => 'goldendoodle',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => NULL,
                'max_life' => NULL,
                'male_weight_max' => NULL,
                'male_weight_min' => NULL,
                'female_weight_max' => NULL,
                'female_weight_min' => NULL,
                'content' => NULL,
            'history_description' => '<p>The Goldendoodle is recognized for its cheerful disposition and intelligence, making it a favorite among families, therapy, and assistance dogs. This hybrid breed combines the friendly and sociable personality of the Golden Retriever with the intelligence and trainability of the Poodle. They come in various sizes based on the type of Poodle used in the breeding (Standard, Miniature, or Toy).</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>Goldendoodles come in three main sizes, depending on the size of the Poodle parent:</p><ul><li><strong>Standard Goldendoodle</strong>: Typically weighs between 50 to 90 pounds (23 to 41 kg) and stands about 20 to 24 inches (51 to 61 cm) tall.</li><li><strong>Miniature Goldendoodle</strong>: Usually weighs between 25 to 50 pounds (11 to 23 kg) and stands about 16 to 20 inches (41 to 51 cm) tall.</li><li><strong>Toy Goldendoodle</strong>: Generally weighs around 10 to 25 pounds (5 to 11 kg) and stands about 10 to 16 inches (25 to 41 cm) tall.</li></ul>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The coat of a Goldendoodle can vary depending on whether it inherits more from the Poodle or the Golden Retriever parent. They typically have a wavy or curly coat that is low-shedding and considered hypoallergenic, making them a good choice for allergy sufferers. Common coat colors include cream, gold, apricot, and red. Regular grooming is necessary to prevent matting and to maintain coat health, especially for those with curlier coats.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Goldendoodles are known for their friendly, affectionate, and outgoing temperament. They are intelligent and eager to please, which makes them highly trainable. Goldendoodles are typically good with children and other pets, making them excellent family companions. Their sociable nature means they thrive on companionship and can experience separation anxiety if left alone for long periods.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Goldendoodles thrive in active households where they receive plenty of social interaction and exercise. They adapt well to different living situations, including apartments, as long as they get enough daily exercise. Socialization and positive reinforcement training are crucial to helping them develop into well-rounded adults.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Goldendoodles enjoy a wide range of activities that cater to their energetic and playful nature, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks, runs, or play sessions</li><li>Participating in obedience and agility training</li><li>Engaging in fetch, tug-of-war, or other interactive games</li><li>Swimming, as many Goldendoodles love water</li><li>Social outings to dog parks or visits to pet-friendly locations</li></ul><p>Providing regular exercise and mental stimulation is essential for the overall well-being of a Goldendoodle.</p><p>If you’re considering a Goldendoodle as a pet, be prepared for a loving, intelligent, and active companion that thrives on social interaction, training, and family involvement. They make excellent pets for a variety of lifestyles!</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            256 =>
            array (
