                'female_weight_max' => 32,
                'female_weight_min' => 25,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>Golden Retrievers were originally bred in Scotland in the late 19th century for retrieving game from both water and land. Their friendly demeanor, intelligence, and trainability have made them beloved family pets and working dogs in various roles, including therapy, assistance, and search-and-rescue. This breed is known for its adaptability and eagerness to please, making it a top choice for families and individuals alike.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>Golden Retrievers are medium to large-sized dogs. They typically weigh between 55 to 75 pounds (25 to 34 kg) and stand about 21 to 24 inches (53 to 61 cm) tall at the shoulder. Males tend to be larger than females.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>Golden Retrievers are known for their friendly, outgoing, and gentle temperament. They are highly social and thrive on interaction with people and other animals. This breed is known for being patient and tolerant, making them great companions for children. Golden Retrievers are intelligent dogs that are eager to learn, which contributes to their reputation as excellent therapy and service dogs.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Golden Retrievers are known for their friendly, outgoing, and gentle temperament. They are highly social and thrive on interaction with people and other animals. This breed is known for being patient and tolerant, making them great companions for children. Golden Retrievers are intelligent dogs that are eager to learn, which contributes to their reputation as excellent therapy and service dogs.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Golden Retrievers thrive in active households where they receive plenty of exercise, social interaction, and mental stimulation. They do well in homes with spacious yards but can also adapt to apartment living if provided with regular exercise. Due to their social nature, they can become bored and develop behavioral issues if left alone for extended periods.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Golden Retrievers enjoy a variety of activities that cater to their energy levels and intelligence, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks, runs, and playtime</li><li>Participating in dog sports such as agility, obedience, and scent work</li><li>Swimming, as they are natural swimmers</li><li>Engaging in fetch or retrieving games</li><li>Training sessions to learn new commands and tricks</li></ul><p>Keeping a Golden Retriever well-exercised and mentally stimulated is essential for their happiness and well-being.</p><p>If you’re considering a Golden Retriever as a pet, be prepared for a loving and loyal companion that thrives on family involvement, activity, and positive training methods. Their affectionate nature and eagerness to please make them one of the most rewarding breeds to own.</p>',
