                'female_weight_max' => 17,
                'female_weight_min' => 13,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>Originating from Ireland, the Kerry Blue Terrier was initially bred for herding and hunting tasks, as well as for guarding properties. Its historical roles included hunting small game and working as a farm dog. The breed is recognized for its courage, agility, and strong work ethic. Today, the Kerry Blue Terrier is cherished for both its companionship and its abilities in various dog sports.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>Kerry Blue Terriers are medium-sized dogs. They typically weigh between 33 to 40 pounds (15 to 18 kg) and stand about 17 to 20 inches (43 to 51 cm) tall at the shoulder. Males are generally larger than females.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The Kerry Blue Terrier has a distinctive, curly, and water-resistant coat that is soft to the touch. The coat is primarily blue but can range in shades from dark slate blue to light blue. They are considered hypoallergenic, making them suitable for allergy sufferers. Regular grooming is essential to maintain the coat\'s condition and to prevent matting; they require professional grooming every few months and frequent brushing at home.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Kerry Blue Terriers are known for their lively, intelligent, and loyal temperament. They are often described as playful and affectionate with their families, yet they can exhibit a strong-willed and confident personality. Early socialization and training are important to ensure they develop into well-mannered dogs. While they are typically good with children and can be friendly with other pets, they may show a strong prey drive towards smaller animals.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Kerry Blue Terriers thrive in active households and require regular exercise to keep them happy and healthy. They adapt well to various living situations, including homes with yards, but they need daily opportunities for physical activity and mental stimulation. They are not ideal for homes where they will be left alone for long periods, as they may become bored and develop behavioral issues.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Kerry Blue Terriers enjoy a range of activities that cater to their energetic nature, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks, runs, or play sessions</li><li>Participation in dog sports such as agility, obedience, and terrier trials</li><li>Engaging in interactive games like fetch or tug-of-war</li><li>Training sessions to learn new commands and tricks, which also keeps their minds sharp</li><li>Social events, where they can interact with other dogs and people</li></ul><p>Providing regular exercise and mental challenges is crucial for the overall well-being of a Kerry Blue Terrier.</p><p>If you’re considering a Kerry Blue Terrier as a pet, be prepared for a spirited and affectionate companion that thrives on activity, training, and strong social bonds with its family. Their unique personality and striking appearance make them a wonderful addition to the right household.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => true,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            260 =>
            array (
                'id' => 284,
                'name' => 'Bull Terrier',
                'slug' => 'bull-terrier',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 15,
                'male_weight_max' => 22,
                'male_weight_min' => 18,
                'female_weight_max' => 20,
                'female_weight_min' => 16,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Bull Terrier originated in England in the 19th century, initially bred for bull-baiting and later as a companion dog. The breed is characterized by its egg-shaped head and muscular build. Bull Terriers are known for their spirited demeanor, confidence, and loyalty to their families. There are two main varieties of Bull Terriers: the Standard Bull Terrier and the Miniature Bull Terrier, both of which share similar traits but differ in size.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<ul><li><strong>Standard Bull Terrier</strong>: Typically weighs between 50 to 70 pounds (23 to 32 kg) and stands about 21 to 22 inches (53 to 56 cm) tall at the shoulder.</li><li><strong>Miniature Bull Terrier</strong>: Generally weighs between 35 to 50 pounds (16 to 23 kg) and stands about 10 to 14 inches (25 to 36 cm) tall.</li></ul><p><br></p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The Bull Terrier has a short, dense, and weather-resistant coat that lies flat against the body. Common coat colors include white, black, brindle, fawn, and combinations of these colors. The coat is low-maintenance, requiring minimal grooming beyond regular brushing to control shedding and maintain cleanliness.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Bull Terriers are known for their playful, friendly, and spirited temperament. They are affectionate and loyal to their families, often forming strong bonds with their owners. While they can be stubborn and independent, they are also intelligent and can be trained with positive reinforcement methods. Early socialization and training are essential to encourage well-mannered behavior, especially because they can sometimes exhibit a strong prey drive or be dominant with other dogs.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Bull Terriers thrive in active households where they receive consistent exercise and mental stimulation. They do well in homes with yards where they can run and play, but they can also adapt to apartment living if provided with regular opportunities for physical activity. They can be prone to separation anxiety if left alone for long periods, so they enjoy being part of family activities.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Bull Terriers enjoy a variety of activities that cater to their energetic and playful nature, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks, runs, or play sessions in the yard or park</li><li>Participation in obedience training and socialization classes</li><li>Engaging in interactive games like fetch, tug-of-war, or hide-and-seek</li><li>Joining in canine sports such as agility or weight pull, which can help channel their energy</li><li>Exploring new environments during family outings or hikes</li></ul><p>Regular exercise and mental challenges are essential for the overall happiness and well-being of a Bull Terrier.</p><p>If you’re considering a Bull Terrier as a pet, be prepared for a loyal, energetic, and affectionate companion that thrives on social interaction, activity, and training. Their unique personality and loving nature make them enjoyable family pets for those willing to invest time and effort in training and socialization.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
