                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Perro de Presa Canario originated on the Canary Islands, specifically in the 15th century. It is believed to be a mix of the indigenous breeds of the islands and Mastiff-type dogs brought by Spanish conquistadors. Initially bred for working purposes, these dogs were used for guarding livestock, controlling cattle, and serving as loyal companions. The breed faced near extinction in the 20th century but was revived through controlled breeding programs in the late 20th century.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<ul><li><strong>Height:</strong> Males typically stand between 24 to 26 inches (61 to 66 cm), while females are slightly smaller, at about 22 to 24 inches (56 to 61 cm).</li><li><strong>Weight:</strong> Males generally weigh between 110 to 143 pounds (50 to 65 kg), and females weigh around 88 to 110 pounds (40 to 50 kg).</li></ul><p><br></p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The Perro de Presa Canario has a short, dense coat that lies flat against the body. The coat can come in a variety of colors, including fawn, brindle, and black, often with white markings. Regular grooming helps manage shedding and keeps the coat healthy.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>This breed is known for its:</p><ul><li>Confident and calm demeanor, making them natural protectors.</li><li>Loyalty and strong bond with their family members, often being affectionate yet wary of strangers.</li><li>Intelligence and independence, which can translate to a stubborn streak; consistent training and socialization are essential.</li><li>Protective instincts, which make them excellent guardians for homes and livestock.</li></ul>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>The Perro de Presa Canario thrives in active environments where they have space to move and play. They do best in homes with experienced owners who can provide firm, consistent training and structure. Early socialization is vital to ensure they grow into well-mannered adults.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>This breed enjoys a wide range of activities, including:</p><ul><li>Regular exercise, such as walks, runs, and play sessions, to burn off energy and maintain fitness.</li><li>Engaging in obedience training to reinforce commands and strengthen the bond with their owner.</li><li>Participating in protection sports or activities that challenge their intelligence and physical abilities.</li><li>Opportunities for socialization with other dogs and people to develop good behavior.</li></ul><p>Overall, the Perro de Presa Canario is a powerful and loyal breed that requires an active lifestyle, consistent training, and early socialization to make them a well-adjusted companion.</p>',
