            269 =>
            array (
                'id' => 234,
                'name' => 'Caucasian Shepherd Dog',
                'slug' => 'caucasian-shepherd-dog',
                'description' => 'The Caucasian Shepherd Dog is a large and powerful breed of dog from the Caucasus Mountains region. These dogs are large in size, with a thick double coat to protect them from the cold. They have a regal bearing, with a proud and confident demeanor. They are highly intelligent and loyal, making them excellent guard dogs. They are courageous and alert, with an instinct to protect their family and property. They are highly trainable, but require firm and consistent training.',
                'min_life' => 15,
                'max_life' => 20,
                'male_weight_max' => 90,
                'male_weight_min' => 50,
                'female_weight_max' => 70,
                'female_weight_min' => 45,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Caucasian Shepherd, also known as the Caucasian Ovcharka, is a traditional livestock guardian breed originating from the Caucasus Mountains. They have been used for centuries by shepherds in the region to protect flocks from wolves and other predators. Their strong protective instincts and ability to withstand harsh climates contributed to their development as working dogs and guardians in rural communities.</p>',
                'size_description' => '<p>Caucasian Shepherds are large and powerful dogs. They typically have the following size characteristics:</p><ul><li><strong>Males</strong>: 25 to 30 inches tall at the shoulder and weigh between 110 to 220 pounds.</li><li><strong>Females</strong>: 24 to 28 inches tall and weigh between 80 to 180 pounds. Their robust build and impressive stature make them intimidating and effective guardians.</li></ul>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>They have a dense, double coat that provides insulation against cold weather. The outer coat is coarse and straight, while the undercoat is soft and thick. Their coat can come in various colors, including gray, fawn, brindle, and white. Regular grooming is necessary to manage shedding, especially during seasonal changes.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Caucasian Shepherds are known for their loyalty, intelligence, and protective nature. They are naturally wary of strangers and can be territorial, making them excellent guard dogs. However, they are also affectionate with their families and can be gentle with children when properly socialized. Early training and socialization are crucial to ensure they develop into well-rounded companions.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Caucasian Shepherds require a lifestyle that accommodates their physical and mental needs. They do best in rural or suburban environments where they have space to roam and access to a secure yard. They may not be well-suited for apartment living due to their size and need for exercise. Daily exercise and mental stimulation are essential for their overall well-being.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>These dogs are active and enjoy various activities that stem from their working history:</p><ul><li><strong>Daily Exercise</strong>: Long walks, hikes, or play sessions to keep them physically fit.</li><li><strong>Training</strong>: Engaging in obedience training and socialization to enhance their behavior and responsiveness.</li><li><strong>Guarding</strong>: Many Caucasian Shepherds take pride in their role as protectors for their property or livestock.</li><li><strong>Mental Stimulation</strong>: Puzzle toys and interactive games can keep them mentally challenged.</li><li><strong>Social Interactions</strong>: Regular contact with people and other pets helps develop their social skills.</li></ul><p>The Caucasian Shepherd is a loyal and devoted breed that excels with proper training, socialization, and activities suited to their needs and abilities!</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            270 =>
            array (
                'id' => 237,
                'name' => 'American Foxhound',
                'slug' => 'american-foxhound',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 15,
                'male_weight_max' => 34,
                'male_weight_min' => 20,
                'female_weight_max' => 34,
                'female_weight_min' => 20,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The American Foxhound is one of the oldest breeds in the United States, developed in the 17th century from various English hounds brought over by settlers. Initially bred for hunting foxes, they are known for their speed, endurance, and keen sense of smell. Over time, the breed was refined through the introduction of other hound breeds to enhance their traits for hunting and companionship.</p>',
                'size_description' => '<p>American Foxhounds typically stand between 21 to 25 inches tall at the shoulder. Their weight generally varies from 40 to 65 pounds, with males usually being larger than females. They have a lean and athletic build, which supports their role as hunting dogs.</p>',
            'coat_description' => '<p>The American Foxhound has a short, dense coat that is easy to maintain. The coat can come in various colors, including tri-color (black, white, and tan), lemon (light tan and white), and red, among others. Their short hair generally sheds moderately.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>American Foxhounds are known for their friendly and sociable nature. They are generally good with children and enjoy being part of a family. However, they can be independent and may exhibit a strong hunting instinct, which can lead to chasing small animals. Early socialization and training are important to ensure they are well-mannered companions.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>American Foxhounds require a lot of exercise due to their high energy levels. They thrive in homes where they have plenty of space to run and play, ideally with a secure yard. They are also known to be vocal, so it\'s important for them to have outlets for their natural instincts.&nbsp;</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Ideal activities for American Foxhounds include long walks, runs, and playtime in a secure area. They can participate in various dog sports such as agility, tracking, and obedience training. Additionally, engaging them in scent work or hunting-related activities can fulfill their instinctual drive and keep them mentally stimulated.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            271 =>
            array (
                'id' => 239,
                'name' => 'Airedale Terrier',
                'slug' => 'airedale-terrier',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 14,
                'male_weight_max' => 23,
                'male_weight_min' => 20,
                'female_weight_max' => 20,
                'female_weight_min' => 18,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Airedale Terrier, often referred to as the "King of Terriers," originated in the Aire Valley of West Yorkshire, England. Developed in the 19th century, they were initially used for hunting otters and rats and later became known for their versatility as working dogs. The breed gained popularity and was used in various roles, including as police and military dogs during World Wars I and II.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>Airedale Terriers are the largest of the terrier breeds. On average, they stand about 21 to 23 inches (53 to 61 cm) tall at the shoulder and weigh between 40 to 65 pounds (18 to 29 kg). Males are typically larger than females.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>Airedales have a distinctive, wiry, and dense double coat. The outer layer is harsh and straight, while the undercoat is soft and insulating. The coat is commonly tan with a black saddle. Regular grooming is necessary to maintain the coat\'s texture and minimize shedding.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Airedale Terriers are known for their intelligence, loyalty, and playful nature. They are friendly and often good with children and other pets when properly socialized. However, they can be independent and strong-willed, requiring consistent training and socialization from an early age.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>These dogs thrive in active households and do best when they have room to roam and explore. They can adapt to various living situations but benefit from having a yard where they can play. Daily exercise and mental stimulation are essential to keep them happy and healthy.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Airedale Terriers enjoy a range of activities including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks or runs</li><li>Agility training</li><li>Obedience training</li><li>Playing fetch</li><li>Participating in dog sports like flyball and rally</li><li>Socializing with other dogs and people</li></ul><p>Overall, Airedale Terriers make great companions for active families who can provide them with the mental and physical exercise they need.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            272 =>
            array (
                'id' => 242,
                'name' => 'Alaskan Malamute',
                'slug' => 'alaskan-malamute',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 15,
                'male_weight_max' => 39,
                'male_weight_min' => 34,
                'female_weight_max' => 34,
                'female_weight_min' => 25,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Alaskan Malamute is one of the oldest Arctic sled dog breeds, developed by the Mahlemut people in Alaska for their strength and endurance. Originally bred as a working dog, Malamutes were used for hauling heavy sleds and freight, as well as for hunting seals and polar bears. The breed\'s history is closely tied to survival in harsh Arctic conditions, and they have been respected for their ability to work in extreme environments.</p>',
                'size_description' => '<p>Alaskan Malamutes are large, powerful dogs. Males typically weigh between 85 to 100 pounds and stand 25 to 28 inches tall at the shoulder, while females weigh around 75 to 85 pounds and stand 23 to 25 inches tall. Their sturdy build is built for strength and endurance.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>Malamutes have a thick, double coat designed to keep them warm in cold climates. The outer coat is coarse and straight, while the undercoat is soft and dense. Their coat colors range from shades of gray to black, red, and sable, with white markings commonly found on the face, belly, and legs. They shed heavily, particularly during seasonal changes, requiring regular grooming.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Alaskan Malamutes are known for their friendly, affectionate, and loyal nature. They are typically good with families and children, making them excellent companions. However, they can exhibit strong-willed and independent behaviors, which may require patient training. They are not overly aggressive but should be socialized early to manage their high prey drive and assertive demeanor.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Malamutes thrive in active environments where they can expel energy. They are best suited for owners who can provide consistent exercise and mental stimulation. A home with a large yard and outdoor space is ideal, as they enjoy being outdoors. Because of their pack-oriented behavior, they do well with other dogs if properly socialized.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Alaskan Malamutes enjoy a variety of activities, including:</p><ul><li>Sled dog racing and mushing</li><li>Hiking and long walks</li><li>Obedience training</li><li>Weight pulling</li><li>Agility training</li><li>Swimming</li></ul><p>These activities not only help channel their physical energy but also provide the mental challenges they need. Adventurous outings are particularly fulfilling for them, and they enjoy exploring the outdoors with their owners. Regular socialization and exercise are essential for maintaining their health and happiness.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            273 =>
            array (
                'id' => 246,
                'name' => 'American Hairless Terrier',
                'slug' => 'american-hairless-terrier',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 14,
                'male_weight_max' => 7,
                'male_weight_min' => 6,
                'female_weight_max' => 7,
                'female_weight_min' => 6,
                'content' => NULL,
            'history_description' => '<p>The American Hairless Terrier is a relatively new breed that originated in the United States in the 1970s. It developed from the Rat Terrier, a type of working dog known for hunting vermin. The hairless gene was discovered in a litter of Rat Terriers, leading to the breeding of hairless variations. The breed was officially recognized by the American Kennel Club (AKC) in 2016, gaining popularity due to its unique appearance and friendly nature.</p>',
                'size_description' => '<p>American Hairless Terriers are small to medium-sized dogs. They typically weigh between 10 to 16 pounds and stand about 12 to 16 inches tall at the shoulder. They have a slender, athletic build that allows for agility and active play.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>As their name suggests, the American Hairless Terrier does not have fur. Instead, they have smooth, hairless skin, which can be prone to sunburn. Some American Hairless Terriers may have a few patches of hair, especially on their feet or tail. They come in various colors and patterns, including solid, spotted, or brindle. Due to their lack of coat, they require skincare, including sunscreen and moisturizer.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>These dogs are known for their friendly, affectionate, and playful temperament. American Hairless Terriers are intelligent and eager to learn, making them easy to train. They are generally good with families, including children, and enjoy being part of the household. Their alertness also makes them good watchdogs.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>American Hairless Terriers adapt well to different living environments, including apartments or homes with yards. They thrive in active households where they receive plenty of attention and exercise. Because of their affectionate nature, they do best when they are involved in family activities and not left alone for long periods.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>American Hairless Terriers enjoy a variety of activities, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks and playtime</li><li>Obedience training and agility</li><li>Interactive games, such as fetch or hide-and-seek</li><li>Trick training to stimulate their intelligence</li><li>Socialization outings to dog parks or dog-friendly events</li></ul><p>Regular exercise and mental stimulation are crucial for keeping them happy and healthy. Because of their playful and energetic nature, these dogs thrive in environments that provide both physical and mental challenges.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            274 =>
            array (
