                'male_weight_min' => 30,
                'female_weight_max' => 35,
                'female_weight_min' => 25,
                'content' => NULL,
            'history_description' => '<p>The Bouvier des Flandres is a herding dog that originated in the Flanders region of Belgium. Its ancestry can be traced back to the Middle Ages, where it was bred for versatility, working as a cattle drover, farm dog, and companion. The breed played a crucial role in agricultural activities, helping to herd and guard livestock. During the 20th century, the Bouvier des Flandres gained popularity as a family pet and working dog, especially during World War I and II, where they were used for various military purposes. The breed has been recognized by several kennel clubs, including the American Kennel Club (AKC).</p>',
                'size_description' => '<p>Bouvier des Flandres are medium to large dogs, with males typically weighing between 90 to 130 pounds and standing about 24 to 28 inches tall at the shoulder. Females generally weigh around 70 to 100 pounds and stand 22 to 26 inches tall. They are sturdy and powerful, with a rugged appearance that reflects their working background.</p><p><br></p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The breed has a dense, double coat that is weather-resistant, providing protection against harsh conditions. Their coat is typically rough and may come in various colors, including black, fawn, brindle, or a combination of these. Regular grooming is necessary to maintain the coat’s condition and minimize shedding, particularly through brushing to prevent matting.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Bouvier des Flandres are known for their loyalty, intelligence, and protective nature. They are typically confident and good-natured dogs but can also be reserved with strangers. They exhibit strong family loyalty and tend to be gentle and affectionate with their owners, including children. Early socialization and training are essential to help them develop into well-rounded companions, as they can be strong-willed and independent thinkers.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Bouvier des Flandres thrive in active environments and need regular exercise to stay mentally and physically stimulated. They do well in homes with a yard where they can run and play. While they can adapt to different living situations, they are best suited for families or individuals who can provide consistent activity and companionship.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Bouvier des Flandres enjoy a variety of activities, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks, running, or hiking</li><li>Obedience and agility training</li><li>Herding trials or dog sports</li><li>Interactive playtime and fetch games</li><li>Swimming</li><li>Participating in family activities and outings</li></ul><p>These activities help meet their exercise needs while strengthening the bond between the dog and its owner. Ensuring regular exercise, training, and socialization will lead to a happy and healthy Bouvier des Flandres.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
