                'max_life' => 17,
                'male_weight_max' => 7,
                'male_weight_min' => 5,
                'female_weight_max' => 7,
                'female_weight_min' => 5,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Schipperke is a small, spitz-type dog that originated in Belgium, likely in the 16th century. Originally bred as a ship dog, they were used to guard boats and serve as ratters on cargo vessels. The breed evolved from the Leuvenaar, a larger dog type, and over time became known for their energetic and alert characteristics. Schipperkes gained popularity as companion animals and were recognized by various kennel clubs in the early 20th century.</p>',
                'size_description' => '<p>Schipperkes are small dogs, typically weighing between 10-16 pounds and standing about 10-13 inches tall at the shoulder. Their compact and muscular build adds to their sturdy appearance.</p><p><br></p><p><br></p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The breed is known for its distinctive double coat, which is dense and straight. The outer coat is longer while the undercoat is soft and fluffy, providing insulation. Schipperkes can come in various colors, but solid black is the most commonly recognized. Regular grooming is essential to manage shedding and keep their coat health</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Schipperkes are known for their lively, intelligent, and curious nature. They are highly energetic and can be quite mischievous, making them both entertaining and challenging. They are loyal to their families and can be protective, often acting as good watchdogs. While they generally get along well with children, early socialization is important to ensure they develop well-rounded behavior.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Schipperkes thrive in active households where they receive plenty of attention and stimulation. They can adapt to apartment living, but they require regular exercise and mental engagement to prevent boredom and behavioral issues. They do best in environments that allow them to interact and explore.</p><p><br></p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Schipperkes enjoy a variety of activities, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks and play sessions</li><li>Obedience training and tricks</li><li>Participation in dog sports such as agility and flyball</li><li>Interactive games and puzzle toys</li><li>Scent work and other mental challenges</li></ul><p>Providing consistent exercise and mental stimulation is crucial for keeping a Schipperke happy and healthy, as they thrive on activity and interaction with their families.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            279 =>
            array (
                'id' => 262,
                'name' => 'Saluki',
                'slug' => 'saluki',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 14,
                'male_weight_max' => 30,
                'male_weight_min' => 20,
                'female_weight_max' => 30,
                'female_weight_min' => 20,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Saluki is one of the oldest dog breeds, with a history that dates back thousands of years. Originating in the Middle East, particularly in Egypt and the Arabian Peninsula, Salukis were used by nomadic tribes for hunting game, including gazelles and hares. They were revered for their speed, agility, and keen sight, often depicted in ancient art and associated with royalty. The breed has undergone little change over the years and remains a distinct symbol of canine elegance and grace.</p>',
                'size_description' => '<p>Salukis are medium to large-sized dogs. Males typically weigh between 60-70 pounds and stand about 28-30 inches tall at the shoulder, while females are slightly smaller, weighing around 40-60 pounds and standing about 24-28 inches tall.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The Saluki has a short and smooth coat that can vary in color, including cream, fawn, red, and spotted. Some individuals may have a longer feathering on the ears and tails, which adds to their elegant appearance. Their coat is low-maintenance, requiring minimal grooming.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Salukis are known for their gentle, reserved, and affectionate nature. They can be somewhat shy with strangers but are typically good-natured and loyal to their families. While they bond closely with their human companions, they also maintain a degree of independence. Due to their hunting background, they may have a strong prey drive.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Salukis thrive in active households where they receive plenty of exercise and mental stimulation. They can adapt to various living situations, but they do best in homes with access to a large, securely fenced yard. Because they are sensitive and can be prone to anxiety, regular companionship and socialization are essential.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Salukis enjoy a range of activities, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks and runs in open spaces</li><li>Lure coursing, which mimics hunting conditions</li><li>Training sessions focused on obedience and agility</li><li>Fetch and other retrieving games</li><li>Socialization with other dogs and people</li></ul><p>Due to their high energy levels and hunting instincts, engaging Salukis in regular exercise and mentally stimulating activities is crucial for their overall well-being and happiness. They thrive on the opportunity to run and explore, making them excellent companions for active owners.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            280 =>
            array (
                'id' => 264,
                'name' => 'Anatolian Shepherd Dog',
                'slug' => 'anatolian-shepherd-dog',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 14,
                'male_weight_max' => 70,
                'male_weight_min' => 50,
                'female_weight_max' => 70,
                'female_weight_min' => 50,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Anatolian Shepherd Dog is a large, powerful breed that originated in Turkey, where it was developed over thousands of years to guard livestock. Traditionally used by nomadic shepherds, these dogs were bred for their ability to protect flocks from predators such as wolves and bears. They are a descendant of ancient flock guardian breeds and have been recognized for their intelligence, loyalty, and independence. The breed gained recognition outside of Turkey in the late 20th century, particularly in the United States, for their working ability and family companionship.</p><p><br></p>',
                'size_description' => '<p>Anatolian Shepherd Dogs are large and robust. Males typically weigh between 110-150 pounds and stand about 28-32 inches tall at the shoulder, while females usually weigh around 80-120 pounds and stand about 24-28 inches tall. Their imposing size and strength make them effective guardians.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The breed has a short to medium-length coat that is dense and weather-resistant. Common colors include fawn, brindle, and white, often with a black mask or markings. The coat is relatively low-maintenance, requiring regular brushing to manage shedding, especially during seasonal changes.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Anatolian Shepherd Dogs are known for their independence, intelligence, and strong protective instincts. They are loyal to their families and can be reserved or aloof with strangers, making them excellent guard dogs. Their independence means they require consistent training and socialization from an early age to ensure they become well-mannered and responsive companions.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>This breed thrives in environments where they have space to roam and protect, making them ideal for homes with large yards or rural settings. They do not typically adapt well to apartment living due to their size and need for physical activity. Regular companionship and mental engagement are essential to prevent boredom and behavioral issues.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Anatolian Shepherd Dogs can enjoy a variety of activities, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks and outdoor play</li><li>Herding and livestock guardian tasks, if applicable</li><li>Training sessions focused on obedience and commands</li><li>Scent work and tracking exercises</li><li>Engaging in interactive games that stimulate their minds</li></ul><p>Providing consistent exercise and mental challenges is crucial for the well-being of an Anatolian Shepherd Dog, as they thrive on activity, social interaction, and the opportunity to perform their natural guardianship instincts.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
