            281 =>
            array (
                'id' => 266,
                'name' => 'Australian Cattle Dog',
                'slug' => 'australian-cattle-dog',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 15,
                'male_weight_max' => 20,
                'male_weight_min' => 16,
                'female_weight_max' => 20,
                'female_weight_min' => 16,
                'content' => NULL,
            'history_description' => '<p>The Australian Cattle Dog (ACD), also known as the Blue Heeler or Queensland Heeler, originated in Australia in the 19th century. The breed was developed to herd cattle in rugged and harsh environments. Early breeders combined various dog breeds, including the Blue Merle Collie, the Dingo, and other herding breeds, to create a resilient and agile dog capable of managing cattle. ACDs gained prominence due to their working ability and intelligence, and they have since become popular as both working dogs and family pets.</p>',
                'size_description' => '<p>Australian Cattle Dogs are medium-sized dogs. Males typically weigh between 35-50 pounds and stand about 17-20 inches tall at the shoulder, while females usually weigh around 30-50 pounds and stand about 17-19 inches tall.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The breed has a short, dense double coat that is weather-resistant. ACDs are commonly found in blue or red speckled patterns, with solid and patched color variations also seen. Their coat is relatively low maintenance, requiring regular brushing to manage shedding, especially during seasonal changes.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Australian Cattle Dogs are known for their intelligence, loyalty, and high energy levels. They are protective and can be wary of strangers, making them excellent watchdogs. ACDs are highly trainable and require consistent training and mental stimulation to prevent boredom. Their playful and energetic nature makes them great companions for active families, although they can exhibit a strong herding instinct.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>These dogs thrive in active households and require plenty of exercise and mental engagement. They do best in environments where they have space to run and play, such as homes with large yards or access to open areas. ACDs are not well-suited for apartment living unless they receive regular exercise and mental challenges.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Australian Cattle Dogs enjoy various activities, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks, runs, and hikes</li><li>Herding training and trials</li><li>Participation in dog sports such as agility, obedience, and flyball</li><li>Fetch and other retrieving games</li><li>Mental stimulation through puzzle toys and scent work</li></ul><p>Regular exercise and engagement are crucial for keeping an Australian Cattle Dog happy and healthy. With their intelligence and energy, they thrive on activities that challenge both their bodies and minds.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            282 =>
            array (
                'id' => 270,
                'name' => 'Cavalier King Charles Spaniel',
                'slug' => 'cavalier-king-charles-spaniel',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 15,
                'male_weight_max' => 8,
                'male_weight_min' => 5,
                'female_weight_max' => 8,
                'female_weight_min' => 5,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Cavalier King Charles Spaniel has a rich history dating back to the 16th century, closely associated with English royalty. Named after King Charles II, these dogs were bred for companionship and were popular among aristocrats. Their ancestors include toy spaniels and other small breeds, and they were often depicted in paintings of the era.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>Cavaliers are small dogs, typically weighing between 13 to 18 pounds (5.9 to 8.2 kg) and standing about 12 to 13 inches (30 to 33 cm) tall at the shoulder. Their compact size makes them ideal lap dogs.</p>',
            'coat_description' => '<p>Cavalier King Charles Spaniels have a silky, medium-length coat that is soft to the touch. They come in various color combinations, including Blenheim (chestnut and white), tricolor (black, white, and tan), ruby (solid red), and black and tan. Regular grooming is necessary to keep their coat healthy and free of tangles.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>These dogs are known for their friendly, affectionate, and gentle nature. They are good with children and other pets, making them excellent family companions. Cavaliers are social and thrive on human interaction, often forming strong bonds with their owners.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Cavalier King Charles Spaniels are adaptable dogs that can fit various living situations, from apartments to larger homes. They require regular exercise but are also content with leisurely walks. They make great companions for individuals, families, and seniors alike.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Cavaliers enjoy various activities such as walking, playing fetch, and participating in dog sports like agility and obedience. They thrive on mental stimulation, so puzzle toys and interactive games are beneficial. Socialization is also important, so they enjoy visiting dog parks and interacting with other dogs.</p><p>Overall, the Cavalier King Charles Spaniel is a loving and sociable breed that makes a delightful companion for those who can provide attention and care.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            283 =>
            array (
                'id' => 272,
                'name' => 'Welsh Springer Spaniel',
                'slug' => 'welsh-springer-spaniel',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 15,
                'male_weight_max' => 25,
                'male_weight_min' => 18,
                'female_weight_max' => 25,
                'female_weight_min' => 18,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Welsh Springer Spaniel has a long history that dates back several centuries in Wales. Initially bred as a hunting dog, particularly for flushing game, this breed has been valued for its ability to work in water and on land. They were likely used by farmers and hunters for retrieving game. The Welsh Springer is recognized for its distinct characteristics compared to other spaniel breeds, and it has remained relatively unchanged over the years.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>Welsh Springer Spaniels are medium-sized dogs. Typically, they weigh between 35 to 50 pounds (16 to 23 kg) and stand about 16 to 18 inches (41 to 46 cm) tall at the shoulder. Their size makes them well-suited for both indoor and outdoor living, as long as they receive sufficient exercise.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The coat of the Welsh Springer Spaniel is medium-length, water-resistant, and wavy. It features a rich red and white coloration, with the red being a striking shade. Regular grooming, including brushing a few times a week, helps manage shedding and keeps the coat healthy and free from matting.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Welsh Springer Spaniels are known for their friendly and affectionate temperament. They are loyal, intelligent, and eager to please, making them excellent companions. They tend to be good with children and can get along well with other dogs, especially if socialized from an early age. They may have a strong prey drive due to their hunting background, so consistent training is essential.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>This breed thrives in an active environment and needs regular exercise to stay happy and healthy. They do well in homes where they are part of family activities. It\'s important to provide them with enough mental and physical stimulation to prevent boredom and behavioral issues.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>&nbsp;Welsh Springer Spaniels enjoy a variety of activities, including:</p><ul><li>Flushing game and hunting</li><li>Agility and obedience training</li><li>Hiking, running, and swimming</li><li>Playing fetch and retrieving activities</li><li>Participation in dog sports and competitions</li></ul><p>Engaging these dogs in activities that challenge both their physical fitness and mental sharpness is important for their overall well-being.</p><p>If you’re considering welcoming a Welsh Springer Spaniel into your home, be prepared for an active and playful companion that requires regular exercise and training to thrive.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            284 =>
            array (
                'id' => 274,
                'name' => 'German Longhaired Pointer',
                'slug' => 'german-longhaired-pointer',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 14,
                'male_weight_max' => 32,
                'male_weight_min' => 27,
                'female_weight_max' => 32,
                'female_weight_min' => 27,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The German Longhaired Pointer has roots that date back to the 19th century in Germany. Developed to be a multi-purpose hunting dog, this breed was created for various tasks, including tracking, pointing, and retrieving game both on land and in water. It is one of the older German pointer breeds and was specifically valued for its versatility and adaptability in different hunting environments. Today, the breed is recognized for its abilities in hunting as well as its role as a loyal family companion.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>German Longhaired Pointers are medium to large-sized dogs. They typically weigh between 50 to 75 pounds (23 to 34 kg) and stand about 21 to 28 inches (53 to 71 cm) tall at the shoulder, with males generally larger than females.</p>',
            'coat_description' => '<p>The coat of the German Longhaired Pointer is long, dense, and water-resistant, providing protection in various weather conditions. The hair is slightly wavy and has a soft undercoat. Common coat colors include liver (brown), various shades of brown, and roan markings. Regular grooming is necessary to prevent matting and to keep the coat healthy.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>German Longhaired Pointers are known for their friendly, affectionate, and loyal nature. They are intelligent and eager to please, making them highly trainable. They are generally good with children and can adapt well to families, although early socialization and training are important. Their energetic disposition means they thrive in active environments.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>This breed requires an active lifestyle and does best in homes where they can get plenty of exercise and mental stimulation. German Longhaired Pointers are not well-suited for apartment living unless given ample opportunities for outdoor activities. They thrive in homes where they can participate in family activities and have access to open spaces.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>German Longhaired Pointers excel in various activities, including:</p><ul><li>Hunting and fieldwork&nbsp;</li><li>Hiking, running, and long walks&nbsp;</li><li>Participation in dog sports like agility, obedience, and tracking</li><li>Swimming and retrieving games&nbsp;</li><li>Engaging in family outings and adventures</li></ul><p>Providing regular exercise and mental challenges is crucial for their well-being, as they need to channel their energy into productive activities.</p><p>If you’re considering a German Longhaired Pointer as a pet, be prepared for an active, loving companion that thrives on exercise, training, and family involvement.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            285 =>
            array (
                'id' => 278,
                'name' => 'Thai Ridgeback',
                'slug' => 'thai-ridgeback',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 12,
                'max_life' => 14,
                'male_weight_max' => 25,
                'male_weight_min' => 20,
                'female_weight_max' => 25,
                'female_weight_min' => 20,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Thai Ridgeback is a native breed from Thailand, originally used for various purposes, including hunting, guarding, and transportation. They are known for their unique ridge of hair along their back, which grows in the opposite direction to the rest of the coat. This breed has remained relatively unchanged for centuries and is recognized for its independence, intelligence, and versatility.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>Thai Ridgebacks are medium-sized dogs. They typically weigh between 35 to 75 pounds (16 to 34 kg) and stand about 18 to 24 inches (46 to 61 cm) tall at the shoulder, with males generally being larger than females.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The coat of the Thai Ridgeback is short, dense, and smooth, providing protection from various weather conditions. The most common colors include black, blue, red, and brindle. Their distinct ridge of hair is a hallmark of the breed, and regular grooming is minimal, usually requiring occasional brushing to remove loose hair.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Thai Ridgebacks are known for their strong, loyal, and intelligent temperament. They can be independent and may show a dominant streak, so early training and socialization are essential. They are typically reserved and aloof with strangers but are very devoted to their families. This breed requires consistent leadership and mental stimulation to thrive.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Thai Ridgebacks are active dogs that need regular exercise to maintain their health and happiness. They are best suited for homes with ample outdoor space where they can play and explore. While they can adapt to various living situations, they do not do well if left alone for long periods, as they may become bored and exhibit destructive behaviors.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Thai Ridgebacks enjoy a variety of activities to keep them physically and mentally stimulated, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks, runs, or jogs</li><li>Agility and obedience training&nbsp;</li><li>Participating in dog sports and competitions</li><li>Interactive play sessions, such as fetch or tug-of-war</li><li>Exploration and outdoor adventures</li></ul><p>Keeping a Thai Ridgeback engaged and active is crucial for their well-being.&nbsp;</p><p>If you’re considering a Thai Ridgeback for a pet, be prepared for a loyal, intelligent companion that thrives on activity, consistent training, and strong leadership. They are well-suited to experienced dog owners who understand the needs of this unique and independent breed.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            286 =>
            array (
                'id' => 280,
                'name' => 'American Bully',
                'slug' => 'american-bully',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => NULL,
                'max_life' => NULL,
                'male_weight_max' => NULL,
                'male_weight_min' => NULL,
                'female_weight_max' => NULL,
                'female_weight_min' => NULL,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The American Bully is a relatively new breed, officially recognized in the early 2000s. It was developed as a companion dog from the American Pit Bull Terrier and several bully breeds to enhance temperament while maintaining the muscular build characteristics of the original breeds. American Bullies are known for their friendly disposition and versatility as family pets, often excelling in roles like therapy and service dogs.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>American Bullies come in various sizes, categorized into four main classes:</p><ul><li><strong>Standard</strong>: Typically weighs between 70 to 100 pounds (32 to 45 kg) and stands about 17 to 20 inches (43 to 51 cm) tall.</li><li><strong>Classic</strong>: Similar in weight to the Standard but with a leaner appearance, standing around 17 to 20 inches (43 to 51 cm).</li><li><strong>Pocket</strong>: Smaller in stature, usually weighing between 60 to 80 pounds (27 to 36 kg) and standing about 14 to 17 inches (36 to 43 cm) tall.</li><li><strong>XL</strong>: Larger than the Standard class, typically weighing 90 to 120 pounds (41 to 54 kg) and standing about 20 to 23 inches (51 to 58 cm) tall.</li></ul>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The American Bully has a short, smooth coat that is easy to maintain. The coat can come in a variety of colors and patterns, including solid, brindle, and multi-colored options. Regular brushing helps manage shedding and keeps the coat healthy.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>American Bullies are known for their friendly and affectionate temperament. They are typically good-natured, loyal, and protective of their families. Despite their muscular appearance, they are known to be gentle and loving, especially towards children. Socialization and training from an early age are crucial to ensure they develop into well-mannered pets. Their confidence and playful personality often make them great companions.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>American Bullies thrive in environments where they receive consistent exercise, training, and social interaction. They adapt well to various living situations, including houses and apartments, as long as they get enough physical activity. They may exhibit a strong bond with family and can be prone to separation anxiety if left alone for extended periods.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>The American Bully is a relatively new breed, officially recognized in the early 2000s. It was developed as a companion dog from the American Pit Bull Terrier and several bully breeds to enhance temperament while maintaining the muscular build characteristics of the original breeds. American Bullies are known for their friendly disposition and versatility as family pets, often excelling in roles like therapy and service dogs.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => false,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
            287 =>
            array (
                'id' => 282,
                'name' => 'Bichon Frise',
                'slug' => 'bichon-frise',
                'description' => NULL,
                'min_life' => 14,
                'max_life' => 16,
                'male_weight_max' => 5,
                'male_weight_min' => 3,
                'female_weight_max' => 5,
                'female_weight_min' => 3,
                'content' => NULL,
                'history_description' => '<p>The Bichon Frise is a small breed that has roots tracing back to the Mediterranean region, particularly as far back as the 14th century. Originally bred as companion dogs, Bichons were popular among nobility and eventually became beloved family pets globally. They are known for their playful nature and strong bond with their families, often excelling in roles as loving companions and therapy dogs.</p>',
            'size_description' => '<p>Bichon Frises are small dogs. They typically weigh between 12 to 18 pounds (5 to 8 kg) and stand about 9.5 to 11.5 inches (24 to 29 cm) tall at the shoulder. Their small size makes them well-suited for a variety of living environments, including apartments.</p>',
                'coat_description' => '<p>The Bichon Frise is famous for its soft, curly coat, which is fluffy and often described as “powderpuff-like.” The coat is usually white but can have cream or apricot shades on the ears or body. They are considered hypoallergenic, making them a good choice for allergy sufferers. Regular grooming is essential to prevent mats and tangles; a professional grooming session every 4 to 6 weeks is recommended, along with frequent at-home brushing.</p>',
                'temperament_description' => '<p>Bichon Frises are known for their friendly, playful, and affectionate temperament. They are social dogs that thrive on human interaction and are generally good with children and other pets. Their cheerful nature and intelligence make them easy to train, but they can sometimes exhibit a bit of stubbornness.</p>',
                'lifestyle_description' => '<p>Bichon Frises adapt well to various living situations, including apartments and homes with or without yards. They require a moderate amount of exercise, typically enjoying daily walks and playtime. Being prone to separation anxiety, they benefit from companionship and should not be left alone for long periods.</p>',
                'activities_description' => '<p>Bichon Frises enjoy a variety of activities that keep them physically and mentally stimulated, including:</p><ul><li>Daily walks and play sessions&nbsp;</li><li>Engaging in interactive games, such as fetch or hide-and-seek&nbsp;</li><li>Socializing with other dogs and people, as they love to be around others&nbsp;</li><li>Participating in dog agility or obedience training, which also helps to strengthen the bond with their owners&nbsp;</li><li>Attending puppy classes, which are great for socialization and learning basic commands</li></ul><p>Regular activities and social interaction are important for the overall happiness and well-being of the Bichon Frise.</p><p>If you’re considering a Bichon Frise as a pet, be prepared for a lively, loving companion that thrives on attention, companionship, and engaging activities. Their playful nature and dedication to their families make them wonderful pets for all types of households.</p>',
                'hypoallergenic' => true,
                'created_at' => '2024-11-14 22:09:53',
                'updated_at' => '2024-11-14 22:13:17',
            ),
        ));


